            <span class="who">
                <span class="">Judah Golen</span>:
            </span>
            <span class="utterance" who="#golenJ" start="3557.114" end="x">She can go to Haifa and buy herself a new hat and a new dress if the money is enough for that. And . . . I mean there is private property in the <a class="term" href="#vothG_kibbutz">kibbutz</a>. If you come . . . if you go into a room of a family in the <a class="term" href="#vothG_kibbutz">kibbutz</a> every member tries to decorate his own room according to his own taste and if he has the ability to buy things a make his room richer, look richer, then he can do it and it's his own property. When he leaves the <a class="term" href="#vothG_kibbutz">kibbutz</a> he can take it with him. But in general, people do not have money in the <a class="term" href="#vothG_kibbutz">kibbutz</a> because they have no need of money. They get everything they need from the <a class="term" href="#vothG_kibbutz">kibbutz</a> itself.</span>
        </li>
                <li>
            <span class="who">
                <span class="">David Boder</span>:
            </span>
